			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I wanted to add something to the above thoughts ... it goes like this ...
<br />

<br />
If you have X and Y, what is the resulting effectiveness?
<br />

<br />
And now you can add values to the equation. Let's say that X is 4 and Y is 5 ... the total, let's say is 20, when you multiply things. Conversely, what happens when X is 5 and Y is 4? The SAME result! 
<br />

<br />
And this is the thing that I usually mention when it comes to stats. It is kinda redundant and silly when you can hit hard, but you hit many times less than otherwise, to make the numbers come out. In the end, these things are all computerized mathematics, and each class is preset for a certain amount of damage, based on their ability to take it ... and it all has to "balance out" to a level number, let's say zero. In other words, the end result is the same. A Wiz may have a 10 in damage, but he has only a 2 in Armor Fact to make up for it, and the result is the same. Where you end up placing the points in the stats in the end, is about the same all around, and the people that have made these games have not learned to play with the mathematics beyond a mere chord change, or Variations Upon The Same Theme. The designs would be much more interesting and different, if they could get away from these equations some, and work on the artistic definition and design of these classes so that they would be more than equitable, and even, at higher levels. EQ messed up really big in this area when Kunark came out, and one can only hope that Mythic won't repeat the same mistakes ... but when it says "Rhyme of Nature 2" on the song, and the blinking Icon says "Rhyme of Earth" it can get scary!
<br />

<br />
Bards, are a conglomeration of abilities and making them a balanced class is tough, and I accept that. However, there is no gain as a Bard in this game, or EQ, if you use one style over the other ... to the point where most Bards in EQ are "tanking" Bards, with the exception of very high levels, and these are old time folks that have been in the game a long time, and know the songs and specs too well, to make a mistake. I mean, it's no secret that Charisma is the difference why you can Charm kite in EQ as opposed to not. Hard to imagine that a Giant likes Charisma, but it tells you that 90 Charisma has a 12 percent larger rate of success than 80 Charisma, when it comes to Charming ... and this is the same in DAoC ... meaning that you will not be able to do all the far out things that the class can do, and will get bored later in the game. 
<br />

<br />
And this is the danger in the definition of the class. When we have 3 roads to choose from, in the Specializations ... one is not even a Specialization (Music) ... the adjustments of your stats are kinda important. Like, what do you need Strength for if you are going to play the Lute and Heal? What do you need the points in Strength for if you are going to Mez, and Sleep all the mobs? If you want to Charm, and Mez, that other specialization would suggest that you need the points in Charisma for success, but I can not tell you yet, clearly, that Mythic has this all down yet. I don't think they do, since there are massive errors in the songs/spells right now, and I am not convinced that some are working right, probably because of the instrument bugs. No instruments yet.
<br />

<br />
But you know that a Hibernian Bard can tank. You know that the Albion Minstrel can NOT tank! And the other Skald is the averaged out one, or the equivalent of EQ's Half Elf.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
